    "These challenges, which focus on developing algorithms for converting RGB images into hyperspectral images, utilize benchmark datasets such as NTIRE-2018 (Arad et al. 2018), NTIRE-2020 (Arad et al. 2020), NTIRE-2022 (Arad et al. 2022), iCVL (Arad and Ben-Shahar 2016), CAVE (Yasuma et al. 2010), NUS (Nguyen et al. 2014), Harvard (Chakrabarti and Zickler 2011), and KAUST-HS (Li et al. 2021) to evaluate and enhance algorithm performance.",
    "Each dataset provides a unique test environment with varying spectral bands (400-730 nm), resolutions, and scenarios, ranging from the progressively expanding NTIRE series to the specific setups of CAVE and Harvard, thereby aiding in the thorough assessment and improvement of spectral reconstruction techniques.",
    "Further exploration of these algorithms reveals a categorization into general neural network structures (depicted in Fig. 2), which are detailed in subsequent sub-sections based on their configura-1 3",
    "tion and functionality and the performance of these algorithms on the benchmark dataset are listed in Table 1.",
    "3.3.1.1 HSCNN HSCNN, an innovative deep-learning model, leverages the structure of the very deep CNNs for super-resolution (VDSR) architecture, initially designed for enhancing spatial resolution, to transform RGB and compressed-sensor images into hyperspectral data (Xiong et al. 2017)."
  ],
